  "expert_review": {
    "design_styling": "Replacing the California T, the Portofino wasn’t merely an iteration; it was a revolution in design language. At the front, the car showcased a series of cleverly placed vents and air ducts. These design features played a significant role in maintaining optimal engine temperatures while ensuring downforce. The real magic, however, was in its proportions. The elongated hood complemented the more compact rear, evoking that quintessential sports car silhouette. Unlike the California’s somewhat awkward rear-end, the Portofino perfected it. With its quad exhausts, integrated spoiler, and a rear diffuser, the back of the Portofino was a masterpiece in itself."
  },
  "verdict": "The Ferrari Portofino isn't the fastest, best handling or loudest supercar out there. But for what it is meant to do i.e. look good while being drivable enough to be used every day, it is nearly perfect. The roof mechanism could be better engineered to take real life problems like dust. We still think it is the prettiest car out there today and considering the fact that it is the entry-level vehicle in the Ferrari lineup, expect it to sell like hot cakes.",
